# VisionBoard Backend — Comprehensive Implementation Plan

## Problem Statement

The VisionBoard habit tracker currently stores all data in the browser's `localStorage` via Zustand's `persist` middleware. This means:

- **Data loss** if the user clears browser storage or switches devices
- **No multi-device sync** — habits on laptop aren't visible on phone
- **No user accounts** — anyone accessing the URL sees the same (empty) state
- **No data analytics** — impossible to build server-side insights or reports

This plan adds a production-grade backend with authentication, persistent storage, and a test-driven approach.

---

## Tech Stack & Justification

### Evaluated Alternatives

Before arriving at the final stack, here's why certain alternatives were rejected:

| Alternative | Rejected Because |
|---|---|
| **Separate Express.js server** | Adds deployment complexity, CORS handling, and a second hosting target. The Next.js app can host API routes natively, keeping everything in one deployment |
| **Supabase / Firebase** | Vendor lock-in, less control over schema design, adds external dependency costs. For a personal/portfolio project, self-hosted MongoDB gives full control |
| **Prisma (SQL)** | The `completions` field is a flexible date→boolean map that fits naturally in a document model. Prisma+SQL would need a separate `completions` table with joins, adding query complexity |
| **tRPC** | Great for type safety, but adds significant learning curve and boilerplate. For a CRUD app with 12 endpoints, standard REST is simpler and more universally understood |
| **Passport.js** | Heavy, plugin-based. NextAuth.js is purpose-built for Next.js and handles session/JWT/providers out of the box |

### Chosen Stack

| Layer | Technology | Version | Why |
|---|---|---|---|
| **API Layer** | Next.js App Router (Route Handlers) | 16.1.7 (already installed) | Zero additional infrastructure — API routes live alongside UI. Same deployment, same domain, no CORS. Supports middleware, edge runtime, and streaming |
| **Database** | MongoDB Atlas (free tier) | 8.x | Document model naturally maps to our data shapes (`completions` as a nested object). Free tier gives 512MB — more than enough for habit tracking. No schema migrations needed |
| **ODM** | Mongoose | 8.x | Schema validation at the application layer, built-in TypeScript support, middleware hooks for pre/post operations, population for relational references |
| **Authentication** | NextAuth.js (Auth.js v5) | 5.x | First-class Next.js integration, built-in JWT + session management, supports credentials provider (email/password) and OAuth (GitHub, Google) for future expansion |
| **Password Hashing** | bcryptjs | 2.x | Pure JS implementation (no native bindings), works everywhere including serverless. Resistant to timing attacks, configurable salt rounds |
| **Validation** | Zod | 3.x | Already used by Shadcn/ui ecosystem, TypeScript-first schema validation, generates types from schemas, great error messages |
| **Testing** | Jest + Supertest + mongodb-memory-server | 29.x / 7.x / 10.x | Industry standard for Node.js testing. `mongodb-memory-server` spins up an in-memory MongoDB for fast, isolated test runs — no external DB needed for CI |
| **HTTP Client** | Native `fetch` | Built-in | Next.js 16 has enhanced `fetch` with caching/revalidation. No need for Axios — reduces bundle size |

### Why NOT a Separate Express Server

The previous conversation planned a separate `server/` Express project. Here's why we should use **Next.js Route Handlers** instead:

```
Express Approach (2 projects):          Next.js Route Handlers (1 project):
┌──────────────┐  ┌──────────────┐     ┌──────────────────────────────┐
│  Next.js UI  │──│  Express API │     │  Next.js UI + API Routes     │
│  port 3000   │  │  port 5000   │     │  port 3000                   │
│  Vercel/etc  │  │  Railway/etc │     │  Single Vercel deployment    │
└──────────────┘  └──────────────┘     └──────────────────────────────┘
   ❌ CORS config    ❌ 2 deployments      ✅ No CORS  ✅ 1 deployment
   ❌ 2 package.json ❌ 2 CI pipelines     ✅ Shared types ✅ 1 pipeline
```

