## Database Schema Design

### User Collection

```typescript
// Schema: users
{
  _id: ObjectId,
  name: string,                    // display name
  email: string,                   // unique, indexed, lowercase
  passwordHash: string,            // bcrypt hash (12 rounds)
  createdAt: Date,                 // auto-set
  updatedAt: Date                  // auto-set
}
// Indexes: { email: 1 } (unique)
```

### Habit Collection

```typescript
// Schema: habits
{
  _id: ObjectId,
  userId: ObjectId,                // ref → users, indexed
  name: string,                    // e.g. "Drink water"
  emoji: string,                   // e.g. "💧"
  frequency: "daily" | "weekly",
  completions: Map<string, boolean>, // "2026-03-17" → true
  createdAt: Date,
  updatedAt: Date
}
// Indexes: { userId: 1 }, { userId: 1, createdAt: -1 }
```

### RoutineItem Collection

```typescript
// Schema: routine_items
{
  _id: ObjectId,
  userId: ObjectId,                // ref → users, indexed
  period: "morning" | "afternoon" | "evening",
  name: string,
  timeEstimate: number | null,     // minutes
  sortOrder: number,
  completions: Map<string, boolean>, // "2026-03-17" → true
  createdAt: Date,
  updatedAt: Date
}
// Indexes: { userId: 1, period: 1, sortOrder: 1 }
```

### Why This Schema Design

1. **`completions` as a Map** — Matches the existing frontend `Record<string, boolean>` exactly. No transformation needed when sending data to the client. MongoDB handles sparse maps efficiently
2. **`userId` on every document** — Enables simple `find({ userId })` queries with index coverage. No expensive joins
3. **`sortOrder` on RoutineItem** — Enables drag-and-drop reorder without rewriting all documents (just swap `sortOrder` values)

